A series of solutions with varying concentrations of curcumin (0.25 ​mg/ml to 0.82 ​mg/ml) were added to Pom extract (0.5 ​μM) (Fig. 7
                     ). The pH of Pom extract used here is 6. When curcumin was added to Pom extract, the polyphenolic band at 420 ​nm shows a gradual decrease and the peak of curcumin at 550 ​nm shifts towards blue wavelength side and the peak of anthocyanins around 650 ​nm gradually increases (Table 1
                     ). Change in the emission band of pom extract is primarily due to the influence of curcumin.

In order to study the FRET process using Pom-CAg NP mixture, change in the emission spectra was observed with the addition of CAg NP (0.10 mg/ml-0.45 ​mg/ml) to Pom extract at pH 6.0 (Fig. 9
                     ). On increasing the amount of CAg NP to Pom (0.5 ​μM), the emission of polyphenols at 440 ​nm shifts to 409 ​nm with a gradual decrease in the intensity. A peak around 500 ​nm appears with increasing the intensity upon addition of CAg NP from 0 to 0.45 ​mg/ml (Table 2
                     ). There is a gradual increase in the emission band of anthocyanin band around 600 ​nm. Fig. 10
                      shows the CIE plot of Pom-CAg NP.

Pom-CAg NP-PVA mixture was also used in the production of white light. When CAg NP-PVA was added to pom extract emission band of polyphenol decreases, CAg NP-PVA increases and the emission band of anthocyanin ranging from 545 ​nm to 680 ​nm increases (Fig. 11
                     ). Also, there is a shift in the emission peak of polyphenol, and CAg NP-PVA. This shows the possibility of FRET from polyphenols to CAg NP-PVA and then to anthocyanins. Here in this case, the absorption of curcumin and absorption of anthocyanin overlap with the emission of CAg NP-PVA. Variation in the emission intensity shows the loss in the emission of polyphenols and decrease in the emission intensity of CAg NP-PVA. Decrease in the intensity of curcumin is used up for the increase in the emission intensity of anthocyanin. Presence of FRET in pom-curcumin mixture results in a broad emission spectrum (ie, from 400 ​nm to 700 ​nm). Variation in the colour coordinates obtained from the combination of Pom and CAgNP-PVA is shown in Table 3
                     .
